// The `prelude.json` sub-module: the JSON boundary, over PLAIN Katari values. A JSON document is not a
// dedicated tree type â€” it is an ordinary value: a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean /
// null (the "document shape"). A program traverses a parsed reply with shape filters (`case record(r)` /
// `case array(a)` / `case string(s)`) and the total readers below, and builds one with ordinary record /
// array literals. Referenced by the default-import qualifier: `json.parse(...)`, `json.field(...)`.
//
// A value renders to / from bare JSON through ONE codec, shared with the FFI boundary. Every reserved wire
// key lives in the `$katari_` namespace (a `file` is `{ $katari_ref: id }`, a `data` value is
// `{ $katari_constructor: name, $katari_value: { ...fields } }`, an agent / closure / tool its own handle
// object), which a program never authors â€” so a bare record needs no escaping, and the reserved keys are
// disjoint from any document a program writes.
//
//   - `parse : string -> unknown`      text -> the value it denotes (a `$katari_ref` becomes a `file`, â€¦)
//   - `validate[T] : unknown -> T`     check a value against T's schema (returns it unchanged, or throws)
//   - `parse_as[T] : string -> T`      `parse` then `validate[T]` (the typed text boundary)
//   - `stringify[T] : T -> string`     ANY value -> its (compact, canonical) JSON text
//
// `parse` and `stringify` are inverses through that codec: a document (record / array / scalar) round-trips
// verbatim, so `stringify(parse(s)) == s` (modulo whitespace / number normalisation). `parse` interprets the
// `$katari_` markers â€” external JSON never carries such a key, so a real document is unaffected â€” and a
// `file` / `data` / callable value likewise stringifies to its handle object. `stringify` is TOTAL and
// CANONICAL (one value, one text); it is also the READ CHANNEL that lets an AI SEE a handle / data value (an
// error render, a handle embed, a tool result shown back to a model). A secret operand taints the whole
// result (the monotonic information-flow rule).
//
// Errors: malformed text throws `parse_error` (`parse` / `parse_as`); a value that does not conform to the
// requested type's schema throws `validation_error` (`validate` / `parse_as`), naming the offending path.
// `stringify` is TOTAL â€” it never throws.

@"A JSON document failed to parse: the text is not JSON. Thrown by `parse` / `parse_as`."
data parse_error(message: string)

@"A value does not conform to the requested type's schema. Thrown by `validate` / `parse_as`; `message`
names the offending path."
data validation_error(message: string)

@"Parse JSON text into the value it denotes â€” a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null,
or a `file` where the text carries a `$katari_ref` handle. Traverse a document with shape filters
(`case record(r)`) and the readers below, or pin its shape with `parse_as[T]`. A number without a fractional
part parses as `integer`. Malformed text throws `parse_error`."
primitive agent parse(@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> unknown with prelude.throw[parse_error]

@"Check @value@ against T's schema and return it unchanged, or throw `validation_error` naming the offending
path. A pure check â€” it never rewrites the value. Instantiate T explicitly (it appears only in the result,
so it cannot be inferred)."
primitive agent validate[T](@"The value to check against T." value: unknown) -> T with prelude.throw[validation_error]

@"Parse JSON text directly as a T â€” `parse` then `validate[T]`, the typed text boundary. Instantiate T
explicitly (it appears only in the result, so it cannot be inferred). Malformed text throws `parse_error`;
a value that does not conform to T's schema throws `validation_error` naming the offending path."
agent parse_as[T](@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> T with prelude.throw[parse_error | validation_error] {
  validate[T](value = parse(text = text))
}

@"Render ANY value as its (compact) JSON text â€” TOTAL and CANONICAL (one value, one text). A document value
(record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null) round-trips verbatim, so `stringify(parse(s))`
is `s` up to whitespace; a `file` becomes its `$katari_ref` handle object, a `data` value nests its fields
under `$katari_value` (`{ $katari_constructor: name, $katari_value: { ...fields } }`), and an agent / closure
/ tool its handle object. `stringify` is the READ CHANNEL for showing an AI a handle / data value (an error
render, a handle embed, a tool result rendered back to a model). A secret operand taints the whole result
(the monotonic information-flow rule)."
primitive agent stringify[T](value: T) -> string

// The total readers â€” plain Katari over `unknown`, for picking values out of a document of unknown or
// irregular shape (an AI reply, a third-party API response) without a shape filter at every step. The
// subject parameter is named `target`, uniform with the other container lookups (`record.get`,
// `array.get`). Each reader is TOTAL: a missing key, an out-of-range index or a wrong shape yields `null` /
// `""` / an empty container rather than an error, so probes chain freely â€” `text(target = field(target =
// element(target = parsed, index = 0), key = "content"))` â€” and absence is checked once, at the end, where
// it matters. For a document whose shape IS known, prefer the typed boundary (`parse_as[T]`), which
// validates instead of defaulting. Where a genuine shape branch is wanted, use a shape filter
// directly (`match (node) { case record(r) -> ... case array(a) -> ... case _ -> node }`).

@"The record @target@ holds (its entries), or the empty record if @target@ is not a record."
agent entries(target: unknown) -> record[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record_value
    case _ -> record.empty()
  }
}

@"The array @target@ holds (its elements), or the empty array if @target@ is not an array."
agent items(target: unknown) -> array[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array_value
    case _ -> array.empty()
  }
}

@"The child at object key @key@ (`null` if @target@ is not a record or has no such key)."
agent field(target: unknown, key: string) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record.get(target = record_value, key = key)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The element at array index @index@ (`null` if @target@ is not an array or @index@ is out of range)."
agent element(target: unknown, index: integer) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array.get(target = array_value, index = index)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The string @target@ holds (the empty string if it is not a string)."
agent text(target: unknown) -> string {
  match (target) {
    case string(string_value) -> string_value
    case _ -> ""
  }
}
